    },
    {
      "id": "9c4ffc444e16f499afbe4758a9d78d3f18263a5a",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 221,
        "name": "Bruce Korb",
        "email": "bruce_korb@xyratex.com",
        "username": "bkorb",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2013-07-12 13:57:46.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 3:\n\n``Ran 17 tests. 3 tests failed: runtests, conf-sanity, replay-single.''\n\nOf course, this is nonsense.  The commit message checker can only have an effect on testing if the testing relies on the script in some way.  I am willing to believe that that is not possible.  The tests are broken.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 3
    },
    {
      "id": "a4c5cf24a459530fd88546afbfbe75eca27381dc",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2013-07-13 06:53:31.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 3: Looks good to me, approved\n\nFYI, there are currently four different sets of tests run for each patch - regular ldiskfs tests (which must all pass, and provide the Verified or Failed review of the patch), ZFS tests (mostly pass), DNE (mostly pass), and DNE + ZFS (often fail). \n\nWe decided it is better to get results on the failing configurations, even if we don't require them to all pass, so that we can use the results for improving the tests until they DO pass.  You only need to look at the one result that reports Verified or Failed, unless you want to chip in and help fix the other tests as well.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 3
    },
    {
      "id": "9f901f6124aa654f9170ab1dc1cb096742487971",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2013-07-13 06:54:24.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 3:\n\nShould also be cherry-picked to b2_1 and b2_4 as well.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 3
    },
    {
      "id": "5b9cfeb839a4b0ba32a9395689c77d55acc1ad33",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 221,
        "name": "Bruce Korb",
        "email": "bruce_korb@xyratex.com",
        "username": "bkorb",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2013-07-14 14:45:34.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 3:\n\n``We decided it is better to get results on the failing configurations, even if we don't require them to all pass, so that we can use the results for improving the tests until they DO pass.''\nFair enough, but just how hard is it to mark the unimportant/may fail results with a comment that alleviates anxieties of folks not in the know?\n\n``Should also be cherry-picked to b2_1 and b2_4 as well.''\nAny actively maintained branch, or are these all?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 3
    },
    {
      "id": "3e226ec06ff7542085e5971f45c6568e3b79ae2a",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 112,
        "name": "Oleg Drokin",
        "email": "green@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "green"
      },
